#: ../../../faq.rst:355
msgid "Why does ``on_message`` make my commands stop working?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:357
msgid ""
"Overriding the default provided ``on_message`` forbids any extra commands "
"from running. To fix this, add a ``bot.process_commands(message)`` line at "
"the end of your ``on_message``. For example: ::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:360
msgid ""
"@bot.event\n"
"async def on_message(message):\n"
"    # do some extra stuff here\n"
"\n"
"    await bot.process_commands(message)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:366
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can place your ``on_message`` logic into a **listener**. "
"In this setup, you should not manually call ``bot.process_commands()``. This "
"also allows you to do multiple things asynchronously in response to a "
"message. Example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:370
msgid ""
"@bot.listen('on_message')\n"
"async def whatever_you_want_to_call_it(message):\n"
"    # do stuff here\n"
"    # do not process commands here"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:376
msgid "Why do my arguments require quotes?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:378
msgid "In a simple command defined as:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:380
msgid ""
"@bot.command()\n"
"async def echo(ctx, message: str):\n"
"    await ctx.send(message)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:386
msgid ""
"Calling it via ``?echo a b c`` will only fetch the first argument and "
"disregard the rest. To fix this you should either call it via ``?echo \"a b "
"c\"`` or change the signature to have \"consume rest\" behaviour. Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:389
msgid ""
"@bot.command()\n"
"async def echo(ctx, *, message: str):\n"
"    await ctx.send(message)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:395
msgid "This will allow you to use ``?echo a b c`` without needing the quotes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:398
msgid "How do I get the original ``message``\\?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:400
msgid ""
"The :class:`~ext.commands.Context` contains an attribute, :attr:`~.Context."
"message` to get the original message."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:403 ../../../faq.rst:417
msgid "Example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:405
msgid ""
"@bot.command()\n"
"async def length(ctx):\n"
"    await ctx.send(f'Your message is {len(ctx.message.content)} characters "
"long.')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:412
msgid "How do I make a subcommand?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:414
msgid ""
"Use the :func:`~ext.commands.group` decorator. This will transform the "
"callback into a :class:`~ext.commands.Group` which will allow you to add "
"commands into the group operating as \"subcommands\". These groups can be "
"arbitrarily nested as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:419
msgid ""
"@bot.group()\n"
"async def git(ctx):\n"
"    if ctx.invoked_subcommand is None:\n"
"        await ctx.send('Invalid git command passed...')\n"
"\n"
"@git.command()\n"
"async def push(ctx, remote: str, branch: str):\n"
"    await ctx.send(f'Pushing to {remote} {branch}')"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:430
msgid "This could then be used as ``?git push origin master``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:433
msgid "Views and Modals"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:435
msgid ""
"Questions regarding :class:`discord.ui.View`, :class:`discord.ui.Modal`, and "
"their components such as buttons, select menus, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:438
msgid "How can I disable all items on timeout?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:440
msgid "This requires three steps."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:442
msgid ""
"Attach a message to the :class:`~discord.ui.View` using either the return "
"type of :meth:`~abc.Messageable.send` or retrieving it via :attr:"
"`InteractionCallbackResponse.resource`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:443
msgid ""
"Inside :meth:`~ui.View.on_timeout`, loop over all items inside the view and "
"mark them disabled."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:444
msgid "Edit the message we retrieved in step 1 with the newly modified view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:446
msgid "Putting it all together, we can do this in a text command:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:448
msgid ""
"class MyView(discord.ui.View):\n"
"    async def on_timeout(self) -> None:\n"
"        # Step 2\n"
"        for item in self.children:\n"
"            item.disabled = True\n"
"\n"
"        # Step 3\n"
"        await self.message.edit(view=self)\n"
"\n"
"    @discord.ui.button(label='Example')\n"
"    async def example_button(self, interaction: discord.Interaction, button: "
"discord.ui.Button):\n"
"        await interaction.response.send_message('Hello!', ephemeral=True)\n"
"\n"
"@bot.command()\n"
"async def timeout_example(ctx):\n"
"    \"\"\"An example to showcase disabling buttons on timing out\"\"\"\n"
"    view = MyView()\n"
"    # Step 1\n"
"    view.message = await ctx.send('Press me!', view=view)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:470
msgid ""
"Application commands, when you respond with :meth:`InteractionResponse."
"send_message`, return an instance of :class:`InteractionCallbackResponse` "
"which contains the message you sent. This is the message you should attach "
"to the view."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:472
msgid "Putting it all together, using the previous view definition:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:474
msgid ""
"@tree.command()\n"
"async def more_timeout_example(interaction):\n"
"    \"\"\"Another example to showcase disabling buttons on timing out\"\"\"\n"
"    view = MyView()\n"
"    callback = await interaction.response.send_message('Press me!', "
"view=view)\n"
"\n"
"    # Step 1\n"
"    resource = callback.resource\n"
"    # making sure it's an interaction response message\n"
"    if isinstance(resource, discord.InteractionMessage):\n"
"        view.message = resource"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:490
msgid "Application Commands"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:492
msgid ""
"Questions regarding Discord's new application commands, commonly known as "
"\"slash commands\" or \"context menu commands\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:495
msgid "My bot's commands are not showing up!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:497
msgid ""
"Did you :meth:`~.CommandTree.sync` your command? Commands need to be synced "
"before they will appear."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:498
msgid ""
"Did you invite your bot with the correct permissions? Bots need to be "
"invited with the ``applications.commands`` scope in addition to the ``bot`` "
"scope. For example, invite the bot with the following URL: ``https://discord."
"com/oauth2/authorize?client_id=<client id>&scope=applications."
"commands+bot``. Alternatively, if you use :func:`utils.oauth_url`, you can "
"call the function as such: ``oauth_url(<other options>, scopes=(\"bot\", "
"\"applications.commands\"))``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:505
msgid "How do I restrict a command to a specific guild?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:507
msgid ""
"To restrict an application command to one or more guilds, you must register "
"it as a **guild command** instead of a global command. Guild commands are "
"only available in the specified guild(s)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:510
msgid ""
"The most straightforward way is to use the :meth:`~app_commands.guilds` "
"decorator on your command or GroupCog."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:512
msgid ""
"``123456789012345678`` should be replaced with the actual guild ID you want "
"to restrict the command to."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:514
msgid ""
"@app_commands.command()  # or @tree.command()\n"
"@app_commands.guilds(123456789012345678)  # or @app_commands.guilds(discord."
"Object(123456789012345678))\n"
"async def ping(interaction: Interaction):\n"
"    await interaction.response.send_message(\"Pong!\")\n"
"\n"
"# or GroupCog (applies to all subcommands):\n"
"\n"
"@app_commands.guilds(123456789012345678)\n"
"class MyGroup(commands.GroupCog):\n"
"    @app_commands.command()\n"
"    async def pong(self, interaction: Interaction):\n"
"        await interaction.response.send_message(\"Ping!\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:529
msgid ""
"After that, you must :meth:`~app_commands.CommandTree.sync` the command tree "
"for each guild:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:531
msgid "await tree.sync(guild=discord.Object(123456789012345678))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:535
msgid "Other methods to restrict commands to specific guilds include:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:537
msgid ""
"Using the ``guild`` or ``guilds`` argument in the :meth:`~app_commands."
"CommandTree.command` decorator:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:539
msgid ""
"@tree.command(guild=discord.Object(123456789012345678))\n"
"async def ping(interaction: Interaction):\n"
"    await interaction.response.send_message(\"Pong!\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:545
msgid ""
"Adding commands with :meth:`~app_commands.CommandTree.add_command` and "
"specifying ``guild`` or ``guilds``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:547
msgid ""
"@app_commands.command()\n"
"async def ping(interaction: Interaction):\n"
"    await interaction.response.send_message(\"Pong!\")\n"
"\n"
"tree.add_command(ping, guild=discord.Object(123456789012345678))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:557
msgid ""
"Do not combine this method with the :meth:`~app_commands.CommandTree."
"command` decorator, as it will cause duplicate commands."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:560
msgid "Using ``guild`` or ``guilds`` in :meth:`~ext.commands.Bot.add_cog`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:562
msgid ""
"This is mainly for :class:`~ext.commands.GroupCog`, but also works for cogs "
"with application commands. Note: This does not work with hybrid app commands "
"(:issue:`9366`)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:565
msgid ""
"class MyCog(commands.Cog):\n"
"    @app_commands.command()\n"
"    async def ping(self, interaction: Interaction):\n"
"        await interaction.response.send_message(\"Pong!\")\n"
"\n"
"async def setup(bot: commands.Bot) -> None:\n"
"    await bot.add_cog(MyCog(...), guild=discord.Object(123456789012345678))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:575
msgid "Using :meth:`~app_commands.CommandTree.copy_global_to`:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:577
msgid ""
"This copies all global commands to a specific guild. This is mainly for "
"development purposes."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../faq.rst:579
msgid "tree.copy_global_to(guild=discord.Object(123456789012345678))"
msgstr ""
